data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`**. They translate directly to SQL — no entities loaded into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: bulk UPDATE in a single SQL statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
        s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: bulk DELETE in a single SQL statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Key things to know:**

- These bypass the change tracker entirely, so no `SaveChangesAsync()` needed.
- Any already-tracked entities won't reflect the change — call `_db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` afterward if you keep using the same `DbContext`.
- They respect the existing LINQ filters, including global query filters (opt out with `IgnoreQueryFilters()` if needed).
- For the 2M audit log delete, consider batching if your DB has lock/timeout concerns:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
